{
  "text": "BIOTIC FACTORS. Although many entomopathogenic Hyphomycetes are cosmopolitan in soil, very little is known about the saprotrophic ability of most taxa. Much circumstantial evidence suggests that many entomopathogenic Hyphomycetes (e.g. B. bassiana and M. anisopliae) are relatively weak competitors in soil, and it is common to observe relatively restricted vegetative growth emanating from insect cadavers that have died from mycosis in soil (e.g. [CITATION_1] . Supporting this supposition are observations of reduced vegetative growth in soils containing high to moderate levels of organic matter [CITATION_2] and in non-sterilized versus sterilized soils (e.g. [CITATION_3] .",
  "correct_citation": {
