  },
  "bib_entries": {
    "84220135": {
      "title": "Water potential, temperature, and soil type on the formation of Beauveria bassiana soil colonies",
      "abstract": "Abstract Beauveria bassiana hyphal colonies, radiating through the soil from Spodoptera exigua pupal cadavers, attained mean diameters of up to 4.9 cm. In two soils with high organic content, a peat and an artificial nursery soil, the mean diameters attained were 1.3 and 1.6 cm, respectively, at −0.3 bars. Other combinations of soil type and water potential (−0.3 to −37 bars) resulted in colonies with mean diameters ranging from 3.5 to 4.9 cm. Hyphae and conidiophores were not produced on the external surface of the pupal cadavers in soils at −200 bars. At −0.3 bars the growth rate of the colony diameters was 0.07 and 0.08 cm/week in the peat and nursery soils, respectively, and at −37 bars colony growth rates ranged from 0.13 to 0.16 cm/week. Other combinations of soil type and water potential (−0.3 to −15 bars) resulted in colony growth rates ranging from 0.20 to 0.24 cm/week. The colony sizes attained did not change as temperature increased from 13° to 28°C, but colony growth rate was higher at 24°C (up to 0.24 cm/week) than at higher and lower temperatures. B. bassiana strains, ABG-6178 and IL-116, did not differ in the size or the growth rate of the colonies they produced. The primary colonies infected healthy S. exigua pupae in all soil type, water potential, and temperature combinations tested."
    },
    "87741381": {
      "title": "Colonization, transmission, and longevity of Beauveria bassiana and Metarhizium anisopliae (Deuteromycotina: Hyphomycetes) on pecan weevil larvae (Coleoptera: Curculionidae) in the soil",
      "abstract": "Curculio caryae larvae exposed to Beauveria bassiana or Metarhizium anisopliae were held in soil cages for 14 months. After weevil larvae were colonized by B. bassiana, hyphae from the weevil cadavers spread through the surrounding soil and formed colonies up to 8.55 cm in diameter (soil volume, 327.26 cm3). M. anisopliae colonies were restricted to larval cadavers and to the inside of larval soil cells. Adjacent, untreated weevil larvae were sometimes infected and killed by B. bassiana that spread through the soil. B. bassiana colonies reached maximum diameter and threatened adjacent weevil larvae 90 to 120 days after primary larvae were infected."
    },
    "84128416": {
      "title": "Soil antagonism affecting the dose-response of workers of the red imported fire ant, Solenopsis invicta, to Beauveria bassiana conidia",
      "abstract": "Abstract Laboratory experiments conducted under four sets of conditions evaluated the effectiveness of Beauveria bassiana to infect and kill Solenopsis invicta workers. A LC50 of 1 × 106 conidia/ml was estimated for ants directly sprayed with conidial suspensions and subsequently transferred to cups with or without sterile or nonsterile nest soil. A LC50 of 1 × 103 conidia/mm2 was estimated for ants exposed to a plastic surface covered with fungal conidia. When conidia were mixed into nest soil, the LC50 was 1 × 102 conidia/g of sterile soil compared with 2 × 109 conidia/g of nonsterile soil. This suggests that antagonistic factors detrimental to fungal infection were present in the nonsterile soil. LT50s varied between 5.7 and 7.0 days for ants sprayed with 107 and 108 conidia/ml suspensions, respectively."
    }
  }
}